AB  - This article discusses the impact of El Niño on Latin America from 1997 to 1998. El Niño swept away roads and bridges, homes and farms, lives and livelihoods. It created a vast lake in a north Peruvian desert, and ruined the fisheries of Chile. It battered the Pacific-coast resort of Acapulco, Mexico, and lowered water levels, enforcing draught restrictions on ships in the Panama Canal. Overall, the disaster killed at least 900 human beings and livestock by the hundreds of thousands. It hit economies for perhaps $20 billion.
