AB  - The article examines adaptive measures practiced by indigenous Chepang women of Nepal who are negatively impacted by climate change and whose livelihood are at risk of extinction. It discusses in context the socio-cultural and ecological connection between the people, the plant Chiuri (Aesanmdra butyraceae) and wild bats to explain Chepang women's livelihood. Also discussed are measures such as integrated farming and Leasehold Forestry as the women's response to climate change.
