TY  - JOUR
AB  - In hilly tea-growing agro ecosystems such as the Nilgiris district of Tamil Nadu, India, smallholder plantations are increasingly challenged by soil erosion, climate variability, land fragmentation and declining long-term productivity. Agroforestry boundary planting has been promoted as a climate-resilient and spatially efficient land-use option capable of enhancing ecological regulation and livelihood resilience without displacing tea area. Despite its technical feasibility and compatibility with perennial tea systems, adoption of boundary planting remains uneven. Existing research has largely focused on biophysical and institutional constraints, with limited empirical attention to farmers' behavioral decision-making and the translation of adoption intention into actual practice. This study aims to analyze the psychological and innovation-related determinants influencing smallholder tea growers' intention to adopt agroforestry boundary planting and to examine whether adoption intention translates into actual boundary planting behavior. Using an integrated Theory of Planned Behavior (TPB) and Diffusion of Innovation (DOI) framework, the study evaluates how attitudinal factors, perceived behavioral control, subjective norms and perceived innovation attributes shape both adoption intention and realized adoption in a hilly perennial farming context. Primary data were collected from 300 smallholder tea growers across four blocks of the Nilgiris district using a structured behavioral questionnaire. Latent constructs representing TPB and DOI dimensions, adoption intention and actual adoption behavior were operationalized using validated indicators. Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM) was employed to assess measurement reliability and validity, estimate structural relationships and quantify effect sizes, explanatory power (R<sup>2</sup>) and the intention-behavior linkage. The integrated TPB-DOI model explained 67.70% of the variance in adoption intention and 46.20% of the variance in actual adoption behavior. Relative advantage emerged as the strongest predictor of adoption intention, followed by perceived behavioral control and attitude, indicating that growers' decisions are primarily driven by perceived economic, agronomic and risk-buffering benefits and their capacity to implement the practice. Innovation attributes such as compatibility, trialability, observability and perceived complexity significantly influenced intention, although their effect sizes were comparatively small. Subjective norms had no significant effect, reflecting the individualized, site-specific nature of decision-making in perennial, slope-constrained tea systems. Importantly, adoption intention showed a strong and significant positive effect on actual boundary planting behavior, empirically confirming that intention meaningfully translates into realized adoption in this context. By explicitly linking behavioral intention to actual adoption, this study advances agroforestry adoption research beyond intention-based analyses and demonstrates the applicability of integrated behavioral-innovation frameworks in perennial cropping systems. The findings highlight boundary planting as a behaviorally accessible and crop-compatible entry point for agroforestry in hilly tea landscapes. Policy and extension strategies should prioritize enhancing perceived relative advantage, strengthening farmers' implementation capacity, reducing perceived complexity and improving demonstration-based learning rather than relying on normative persuasion. The insights generated are relevant for scaling agroforestry in other land-constrained, perennial farming systems facing similar socio-ecological pressures. [Display omitted] • An integrated TPB-DOI framework explains agroforestry boundary planting adoption decisions within hilly smallholder tea production systems. • Perceived relative advantage and perceived behavioral control emerge as the dominant drivers shaping farmers' intention to adopt boundary planting practices. • Subjective norms exert a limited influence on adoption intention in perennial, slope-constrained tea systems where decisions are highly individualized and site-specific. • Adoption intention shows a strong and statistically significant translation into actual boundary planting behavior, confirming the relevance of intention-based models. • Boundary planting functions as a low-disruption, spatially efficient entry point for agroforestry integration in land-constrained perennial farming systems.
