TY  - JOUR
AB  - In the Philippines, urban definition was anchored on population, density, and socio-physical organization of the city, and town center. However, in 2003 a revision was done to formulate a more practical and realistic definition of urban areas in the country. This new definition highlighted the economic dimension of the urbanization process. The Philippines encountered an urban transition in the first part of the 21st century. Population growth is quite fast with 54 percent living in urban areas and is estimated to reach 111.7 million in 2020.The Philippines is composed of 7,107 islands with Luzon, Visayas and Mindanao as the three largest groups of islands. These groups of islands are further subdivided into 17 regions. One of its regions undergoing rapid urbanization is Region IV-A or CaLaBaRZon which is an acronym for five provinces in southwestern Luzon, just south and east of Metro Manila. CaLaBaRZon is the second most thickly populated region in the country with 67% population living in the urban areas. This is because of its close proximity to Manila and the industrial and economic opportunities that exist there. Thus, CaLaBaRZon is experiencing rapid urbanization, which in the Philippines is a phenomenon that creates opportunities and provides challenges rather than as a threat and burden (Osias, 2008).Looking from the lenses of three urbanization theories (endogenous, modernization and world system), this paper argues that in the country urbanization is more of a burden and a threat particularly in the CaLaBaRZon region. Kuznets claim that urbanization increases inequality in the first stages of industrialization. In addition, Cem Oyvat stated that urbanization changes the overall inequality in a country by raising the impact of urban inequality on the overall distribution. Moreover, urbanization poses enormous challenges already serious: rising urban crimes, expansion of slums, environmental degradation: pollution and vulnerability to flooding (Wan & Sebastian, 2011).So this paper aims to describe and analyze urbanization and its effect in the CaLaBaRZon area. Specifically, it aims to determine the effect of urbanization in inequality, slum formation, crime rate and environmental degradation. Secondary data from National Statistics Office, National Statistics Coordinating Board and other national and non-government agencies were reviewed to come up with an analysis. Results show that urbanization is a burden and a threat because of ineffective governance of local government units (LGUs), inadequate urban development programs and participatory mechanisms, and ill political motivations. Effects of urbanization show that there is increase in the magnitude of poor families, increase in crime rates, and increase in number of families living in slum areas which needs more housing projects. Urbanization also increases the vulnerability to flooding of municipalities surrounding Laguna Lake. This paper recommends strengthening governance capability of LGUs in providing responsive social service delivery and creating employment by optimizing investment opportunities also in the rural areas by boosting and modernizing the agricultural sector while improving urban development programs and intensifying cooperation among LGUs, private sector, civil society, and constituents.
