TY  - JOUR
AB  - Cotton production forms the main livelihood package of rural peasants of Gokwe South. This is due largely to the prevailing climatic conditions that are not well suited for drought prone food-crops such as maize. However, the decline of cotton prices on the world market has destabilised this long cherished and dependable source of livelihood further exposing communities to poverty. This paper, therefore, seeks to illuminate the survival strategies employed by Gokwe South inhabitants in the midst of such a challenge. Guided by the human factor approach, the study was conducted using a mixed methodology, with a sample of 55 respondents. The findings indicated that 90.9% of the respondents had farming as their source of livelihood. Such livelihood sources were largely influenced by factors such as the availability of resources, markets, climatic conditions, and tradition. Income from cotton helped farmers meet basic needs including food and education. Confronted by this existential threat, farmers employed a number of coping strategies including selling livestock, venturing into other crop varieties, and migrating. The study recommends that the government should resuscitate the textile industry in Zimbabwe to enable the local industry to absorb the cotton produced by local farmers, thus reducing the impact of price fluctuations on the global market. There is also need for farmers to form farmers' commodity associations that focus on price negotiation, value addition, and market linkages.
