AB  - Despite the evidence of climate change in Nigeria few studies has sought to understand the vulnerability of rural women to the impact of climate change. The study ascertained the vulnerability of rural women household to climate change hazards on farming communities in Ogun State, Nigeria. A multistage sampling procedure was used in sampling 159 rural women households. Data was obtained with structured interview guide that was pretested with a cronbach-alpha internal consistency of 0.76 for vulnerability of rural women households to climate change hazards. Results were analyzed using frequency, percentages, mean (x), standard deviation, charts, Pearson Product Moment Correlation (PPMC) and Chi-square (?2) test. Result reveals that the mean age was 36years; 70.4% had household size between 3-5 person; 74.2% married; 36.5% had secondary education; mean income was N18, 000 per month while mean farming experience was 9years. Result also indicate 38.4% access information through radio, 39.0% received information on rainfall while 40.9% received climate information on a weekly basis. Furthermore, most of the respondents were of the perception that temperature is changing (x= 2.32), some plants and animal species are no more in existence (x= 2.26) and that storm is more frequent (x= 2.18). In addition, the major effect of climate change were; crop failure (x= 2.28), decrease agricultural productivity and yield (x= 2.42) and food shortage (x= 2.07). Chisquare analysis showed that perception of rural women on climate change was associated with education status (?2 = 13.116, df = 4, P<0.05). Correlation analysis showed significant relationships between perception of women on climate change and age (r = 0.174), farming experience (r = 0.632), farm size (r = 0.553), knowledge (r = 0.308**) at P<0.05. It was concluded that rural women are vulnerable to climate change because it affects their agricultural production. It was recommended that extension workers should intensify effort to bring climate information closer to rural women.
