AB  - The article focuses on the social and economic impacts of climate change on women, particularly in poorer regions of Asia and Africa. Nitya Rao, a professor of gender and development, conducted a study analyzing data from 25 case studies across 11 countries, revealing that climate change exacerbates existing gender inequalities and economic disadvantages. Women, often left to manage households during male migration for work, face increased burdens due to crop uncertainty and limited access to financial resources, as they typically own only 15% of land globally. The study highlights the need for improved access to services and financial support for women, while also noting some grassroots efforts that aim to empower them amidst these challenges.
