TY  - JOUR
AB  - International environmental law is trapped in a quandary. To be effective international environmental law must regulate the activities of non-state actors especially industry actors. Yet, the balance of power between industry actors and states is skewed in many regions of the world with industrial actors yielding greater political and economic power than states where they operate. In the 1970s, developing countries reconsidered their relationships with developed countries and insisted on a "New Economic Order." Now in 2010, the time has come for to promote a "New Environmental Order" based on a newly conceived relationship between business actors and state actors. This paper focuses on the potential for private lawmaking and "bottom up lawmaking" to create solutions to recurring international environmental problems where state action alone has proven ineffective e.g. climate change, declining fishery stocks, and hazardous waste disposal. Some of the great international successes in environmental protection and compliance such as the International Convention on Civil Liability for Oil Pollution are the product of earlier industry efforts (e.g. Tanker Owners Voluntary Agreement concerning Liability for Oil Pollution and the Contract Regarding an Interim Supplement to Tanker Liability for Oil Pollution.) In part, the privatized rulemaking articulated by the private industry agreements provided the necessary legitimacy for future international rulemaking in the field. This paper contributes two proposals to promote meaningful industry involvement in the field of international environmental law. First, the paper proposes developing either new fora or redefining existing fora such as the Business Council for the United Nations or the World Economic to focus on specific informal technical rulemaking that parties agree to comply with based on their good faith agreement (e.g. "gentleman's agreement"). In the trade and investment field, industries have been instrumental in designing some uniform regulatory standards that while not legally binding have nearly universal implementation, e.g. "general understandings" adopted by International Union of Credit and Investment Insurers. Second, in order to translate informal technical rules into binding international law, this paper further proposes that industrial actors whose multinational activities may result in significant transboundary environmental damages be included as full-fledged negotiating parties to emerging international agreements. Companies who produce or trade in certain types of environmentally damaging products are not just stakeholders in a problem but more importantly potential problem-solvers. As public international law is currently envisioned, only diplomats and high level lawmakers create solutions through layers of international law intersecting with domestic law. Industries have adopted a wait and see approach. The combination of active informal rulemaking among public and private actors with the recognition that significant industries should be part of the international lawmaking process contributes important to the formation of a "New Environmental Order." This paper will also address the problems of accountability raised by boosting non-legally binding rulemaking among private industry actors and private participation in public lawmaking. In particular, the paper will examine the challenge of achieving public accountability of environmental standards with the need for timely and decisive action by industries ..PAT.-Unpublished Manuscript
