TY  - JOUR
AB  - In the twenty-first century, total and per capita consumption of fish will increase against an ongoing biological, economic and social crisis in world fisheries. The resolution of this problem is of great significance for humanity. Fisheries provide direct employment for about 250 million people and account for around 20% of the human animal protein supply, yet most stocks are fully exploited or depleted. Fishing is particularly vital in the developing world, where most of the few remaining underexploited stocks are located. Fishing is often the last recourse for those without alternative economic opportunity, and in the coming decades population growth will be concentrated in a narrow littoral zone. This implies profound ethical dilemmas. Who will be permitted to fish? Who will consume fish? Who decides? In the twentieth century, governance evolved rapidly under the influence of technology and markets. There is now a comprehensive architecture for fisheries governance provided by the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea and related instruments, as well as robust institutional support through the FAO, but it is unclear whether this will suffice in avoiding biological and social disaster in the age of globalization. A predicament for policymakers lies in designing and implementing governance systems capable of providing transparency, legitimacy and accountability which will assure compliance and effectiveness. The problem will not be remedied without consideration of the role of fish in the global economy. Fish and seafood have rapidly developed as internationally traded commodities and in coming decades the market itself will likely be the prime mover of governance in fisheries. The sale of fishing rights to foreign transnationals is an attractive option for indebted developing nations seeking hard currency, yet these arrangements are seldom equitable, and as fish becomes scarce and expensive it tends to disappear from the diets of the poor. Is this to be left to the invisible hand? The market is immensely powerful; it can reduce ancient mangrove swamp to fish farm. When the tsunami of 2004 hit Southeast Asia, areas devoted to shrimp aquaculture were devastated because of the absence of this buffer. As Steve Smith argued in his 2003 ISA Presidential Address, this form of structural violence is discounted in mainstream IR theory; death by violent armed conflict is IR while ?death by economics, or by the market is not.? The discipline devotes vast energy to issues such as relative gains; while significant, many topics dear to researchers have little to contribute by way of responding to the stark challenges confronting humanity. At seafood counters throughout the developed world, there is no indication of crisis. Yet in 2001, in the Proceedings of the National Academy of the Sciences, Jeremy Jackson of the Scripps Institution examined human impact upon marine ecosystems and warned that without immediate action, ?absolute microbial domination? of coastal ecosystems within two generations is a distinct possibility. This, and other findings from the physical and life sciences present a signal to the discipline concerning its responsibilities. The objective of this paper is to make a contribution to the ?new normative architecture? of International Relations through an examination of the transformation of regulatory authority in international fisheries and the potential for civil society to mitigate the negative consequences of the global market. ..PAT.-Unpublished Manuscript
